A constellation is an area on the celestial sphere in which a group of visible stars forms a perceived pattern or outline, typically representing an animal, mythological subject, or inanimate object.

The 48 traditional Western constellations are Greek. They are given in Aratus' work Phenomena and Ptolemy's Almagest, though their origin probably predates these works by several centuries. Constellations in the far southern sky were added from the 15th century until the mid-18th century when European explorers began traveling to the Southern Hemisphere. Twelve (or thirteen) ancient constellations belong to the zodiac (straddling the ecliptic, which the Sun, Moon, and planets all traverse). The origins of the zodiac remain historically uncertain; its astrological divisions became prominent c. 400 BC in Babylonian or Chaldean astronomy.

In 1922, the International Astronomical Union (IAU) formally accepted the modern list of 88 constellations, and in 1928 adopted official constellation boundaries that together cover the entire celestial sphere. Any given point in a celestial coordinate system lies in one of the modern constellations. Some astronomical naming systems include the constellation where a given celestial object is found to convey its approximate location in the sky. The Flamsteed designation of a star, for example, consists of a number and the genitive form of the constellation's name.

Other star patterns or groups called asterisms are not constellations under the formal definition, but are also used by observers to navigate the night sky. Asterisms may be several stars within a constellation, or they may share stars with more than one constellation. Examples of asterisms include the teapot within the constellation Sagittarius, or the big dipper in the constellation of Ursa Major.

A constellation is an area on the celestial sphere in which a group of visible stars forms a perceived pattern or outline, typically representing an animal, mythological subject, or inanimate object.

The 48 traditional Western constellations are Greek. They are given in Aratus' work Phenomena and Ptolemy's Almagest, though their origin probably predates these works by several centuries. Constellations in the far southern sky were added from the 15th century until the mid-18th century when European explorers began traveling to the Southern Hemisphere. Twelve (or thirteen) ancient constellations belong to the zodiac (straddling the ecliptic, which the Sun, Moon, and planets all traverse). The origins of the zodiac remain historically uncertain; its astrological divisions became prominent c. 400 BC in Babylonian or Chaldean astronomy.

In 1922, the International Astronomical Union (IAU) formally accepted the modern list of 88 constellations, and in 1928 adopted official constellation boundaries that together cover the entire celestial sphere. Any given point in a celestial coordinate system lies in one of the modern constellations. Some astronomical naming systems include the constellation where a given celestial object is found to convey its approximate location in the sky. The Flamsteed designation of a star, for example, consists of a number and the genitive form of the constellation's name.

Other star patterns or groups called asterisms are not constellations under the formal definition, but are also used by observers to navigate the night sky. Asterisms may be several stars within a constellation, or they may share stars with more than one constellation. Examples of asterisms include the teapot within the constellation Sagittarius, or the big dipper in the constellation of Ursa Major.

Constellations that have captured the human imagination for centuries, providing a sense of wonder and mystery in the night sky. These patterns of stars have been used for navigation, storytelling, and as symbols of cultural and mythological significance. The ancient Greeks, Babylonians, and many other civilizations around the world created their own constellations, each with its own story and significance.

The 88 modern constellations recognized by the International Astronomical Union (IAU) cover the entire celestial sphere and are formally defined by their boundaries. However, within these boundaries, the patterns of stars can often be difficult to discern, leading to subjective interpretations of the shapes and names of the constellations. Nevertheless, they provide a common language for astronomers and stargazers to discuss and study the sky.

The zodiac constellations are a special subset of the modern constellations that lie along the ecliptic, the apparent path of the Sun across the sky. These twelve constellations are associated with astrological signs and are used to track the movement of the Sun, Moon, and planets. However, their origins and meanings remain shrouded in historical uncertainty.

Constellations are not only visually stunning, but they also serve as a useful tool for astronomers to locate and study celestial objects. The names of constellations and their associated stars are used as reference points for astronomical catalogues and star maps. The Flamsteed designation system, for example, uses a star's number and the genitive form of its constellation name to identify its location in the sky.

Overall, constellations represent a beautiful and awe-inspiring facet of the night sky that has captivated humans for millennia. They serve as a reminder of our place in the universe and the importance of mythology, storytelling, and scientific inquiry in our understanding of the cosmos.
